Verenigd Koninkrijk","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"1276–Cir 1318":"1276–1318","1276–1318":"1276–1318","1278–1318":"1278–1318","1260–1295":"1260–1295","1290–1315":"1290–1315","1248–1312":"1248–1312","1245–1278":"1245–1278","Cir 1318":"1318","1 July 1315":"1 July 1315","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1248":"1248","1269":"1269","1312":"1312","1278":"1278","1245":"1245","1276":"1276","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","Stamford, Lincolnshire, England":"Stamford, Lincolnshire, England","Stamford, Kesteven, Lincolnshire, England":"Stamford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Browne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Brown  .","Probably also an Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Braune   or   Braun  .","Irish: phonetic Anglicization of <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhnaigh</b>; see   Breheny  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brown","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: generally a nickname referring to the color of the hair or complexion, Middle English <i>br(o)un</i>, from Old English <i>brūn</i> or Old French <i>brun</i>. This word is occasionally found in Old French, Middle English and Old Norse as a personal name or byname (Middle English personal name <i>Brun</i>, <i>Broun</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Bruno</i>, Old English <i>Brūn</i>, or possibly Old Norse <i>Brúnn</i> or <i>Brúni</i>). <i>Brun-</i> was also an ancient Germanic name-forming element. Some instances of Old English <i>Brūn</i> as a personal name may therefore be short forms of compound names such as <i>Brūngar</i>, <i>Brūnwine</i>, etc. As a Scottish and Irish name, it sometimes represents a translation of Gaelic <i>Donn</i> (see below). <i>Brown</i> (including in the senses below) is the fourth most frequent surname in the US. It is also very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below).","Irish and Scottish: adopted for <b>Ó Duinn</b> (see   Dunn  ) or for any of the many Irish and Scottish Gaelic names containing the element <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired’ (also meaning ‘chieftain’), for example   Donahue  .","Irish: phonetic Anglicization of <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhnaigh</b>; see   Breheny  ."]}]},{"name":"Dorothea","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a post-classical Greek name, from <i>dōron</i> ‘gift’ + <i>theos</i> ‘god’ (the same elements as in   Theodora  , but in reverse order). The masculine form <i>Dorotheus</i> was borne by several early Christian saints, the feminine by only two minor ones, but only the girl's name has survived. In modern use in the English-speaking world it represents either a 19th-century Latinization of   Dorothy   or a learned reborrowing."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":14,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":39,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Dorothea Browne was born in 1276, in Stamford, Lincolnshire, England, her father, Sir John Browne II, was 28 and her mother, Dorthea Swinstead, was 31. She married Benjamin Yieldhall in 1290, in Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1318, in her hometown, at the age of 42